# My little gallery

Machu Picchu in **Peru** is the lost city of the Incas, hidden in the Peruvian Andes. It was likely built in the second half of the 15th century and was discovered in 1911 by the American explorer Hiram Bingham. It served as a place of sun worship and a sanctuary for women known as the Virgins of the Sun. Ordinary people did not live in Machu Picchu. It was reserved exclusively for the elitearistocrats, soldiers, priests, and temple caretakers. Machu Picchu is arguably the most beautiful city ever created by the ancient Inca civilization, filled with stunning gardens and terraces, magnificent structures, and palaces.
![Machu Picchu](https://media.istockphoto.com/id/930824730/pl/zdj%C4%99cie/machu-picchu-peru.jpg?s=612x612&w=0&k=20&c=IniQbZaaMf7bAIblJcK2I6hBOzu7lmxKbrVUvhY46aM=)

Petral in **Jordan** is another set of ancient city ruins, dating back to the 3rd century BCE to the 1st century CE. For hundreds of years, this place was completely unknown, hidden from the world. No one knew of its existence except for the spirits of its original inhabitantsthe ancient Nabataean tribe. Today, Jordan's Petra is one of the world's greatest tourist attractions.
![Petra](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Taj Mahal in **Agra** The "Indian Temple of Love," built in the 17th century by Shah Jahan of the Mughal dynasty, is a flagship attraction featured in virtually every travel guide to India. This white marble mausoleum serves as a tribute and a gift from a grieving husband to his prematurely departed wife, Mumtaz Mahal.
![Taj Mahal](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Chichen Itza in **Mexico** a pre-Columbian Mayan city located on Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula. It flourished between the 10th and 11th centuries CE. After this period, it gradually declined in importance until it was completely abandoned in the 15th century. Despite thousands of years passing since its establishment, the city's structures still stand as a testament to its former glory. The Maya built massive stone edifices in the city, including around 50 temples and structures, the most iconic of which is the Temple of Kukulkan.
![Chichen Itza](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Coloseum in **Rome** Built as the Flavian Amphitheater, it is now known as the Colosseum. A landmark and symbol of the Eternal City, it is the only one of the Seven Wonders of the World located in Europe. The Colosseum was constructed during the reign of Emperor Vespasian between 72 and 79 CE. It has survived wars, disasters, including earthquakes, and narrowly escaped being dismantled by thieves seeking its travertine blocks. The amphitheater was a venue for bloody events and gladiatorial combats.
![Coloseum](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Christ The Redeemer in **Rio de Janeiro** is a 38-meter-tall statue of Jesus Christ, erected atop a granite mountain and the largest of its kind in the world. The monument commemorates the 100th anniversary of Brazil's independence.
![Christ The Redeemer](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Great Wall Of China in **China** is an attraction that ended up in the last position. Not because it disappointed us, but because we haven't seen it yet. We know it stretches nearly 21,196 km and is a symbol of China. Its earliest sections date back to around the 5th-8th centuries BCE and were built to defend against enemies.
![Great Wall Of China](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
